// Making an array:
const colors = ["red", "orange", "yellow"];

// Arrays are indexed like strings:
colors[0]; // "red"

// They have a length:
colors.length; //3

// Important array methods:
//push(value) - adds value to the END of an array
//pop() - removes and returns last value in array

//unshift(val) - adds value to START of an array
//shift() - removes and returns first element in an array


// In JavaScript arrays are dynamic in nature.
-we can add objects at any location.
-concat -- merge arrays.
-includes -- look for a value. // return True or False Value.
-indexof - just like string.indexof
-join - creates a string from an array.
-reverse - reverses an array.
-slice - copies a portion on an array.
-splice - insert or removes/replaces elements.

 let arrDeletedItems = arr.splice(start[, deleteCount[, item1[, item2[, ...]]]])

-sort - sorts an array.


>>[1,2,4] === [1,2,4] are not equal in JavaScript.
due to storage in different loactions.

const array[] // allow changes in array but not in case of variables not change allowed.